C11 / C14 / C17 / C23 changes vs C99 - APExp kencc status
==========================================================

You are right that C89->C99 was the biggest jump. Later standards
add useful features but the deltas are much smaller, and many
features in C11+ are already partially present in kencc/APExp.

References:
  C11:  ISO/IEC 9899:2011
  C14:  ISO/IEC 9899:2014 (mostly defect fixes, no new features)
  C17:  ISO/IEC 9899:2018 (same - defect fixes only)
  C23:  ISO/IEC 9899:2024


=== C11 ===

--- Already done / unneeded ---

A. _Noreturn                        [in APExp: LNRET keyword, lex.c itab]
B. __func__ in all scopes           [done in C99 work]
C. Type-generic math <tgmath.h>     [library: can be implemented as macros]
D. _Thread_local keyword            [in APExp: parsed, mapped to LNAME (stub)]
E. Removal of gets()                [irrelevant for compiler]
F. Removal of implicit int          [kencc already required type specifiers]
G. Alignment: __alignof__ / __alignof  [in APExp: lex.c, GCC-spelling]

--- Not done ---

1. _Static_assert(expr, msg)
   EFFORT: small
   WHERE: cc.y (new statement), cc.h (token), lex.c (keyword)
   NOTE: evaluate expr at compile time (already have constexpr eval for
         array sizes); emit yyerror if false. Very common in ported code.

2. _Alignas(type-or-expr) / _Alignof(type)
   EFFORT: small-medium
   WHERE: lex.c (keywords), cc.y (grammar), dcl.c (attribute on declaration)
   NOTE: _Alignof is like sizeof; _Alignas affects stack layout.
         __alignof__ stub already exists; needs to actually compute value.
         _Alignas for stack variables requires aligning stkoff in adecl().

3. _Generic(expr, type: val, ..., default: val)
   EFFORT: medium
   WHERE: cc.y (new primary expression), com.c (evaluation)
   NOTE: type-generic dispatch; common in tgmath.h and portable headers.
         Must resolve at compile time using type of controlling expression.

4. _Atomic type qualifier and <stdatomic.h>
   EFFORT: large (full implementation) / small (stub)
   WHERE: cc.h (qualifier bit), dcl.c, and a new stdatomic.h
   NOTE: Plan9 has no atomic hardware primitives in APE context.
         Practical approach: stub _Atomic as volatile (correct for
         single-threaded code, acceptable for most ported software).
         Add stdatomic.h with mutex-backed implementations (already
         partially done in atomic.h for musl).

5. Anonymous structs and unions (struct { struct { int x; }; })
   EFFORT: small-medium
   WHERE: dcl.c (struct member parsing), sub.c (field lookup)
   NOTE: Very common in ported code (especially system headers).
         Already partially works in some cases via the existing
         struct layout code; needs systematic support.

6. <uchar.h>: char16_t, char32_t, mbrtoc16, c16rtomb etc.
   EFFORT: small (library stubs)
   WHERE: new sys/include/ape/uchar.h + lib/ap/multibyte/
   NOTE: typedefs only; conversion functions are wrappers around
         existing UTF-8 machinery.

7. Bounds-checking interfaces (Annex K): gets_s etc.
   EFFORT: small (stubs) / skip
   NOTE: Optional annex. Most code uses __STDC_WANT_LIB_EXT1__.
         Low priority; stubs returning EINVAL are sufficient.

8. Analyzability (Annex L)
   EFFORT: skip
   NOTE: Purely informative annex about undefined behavior.


=== C14 (ISO 9899:2014) ===

C14 contains only defect reports and clarifications against C11.
No new language features. No compiler work needed.

--- Done by fixing C11 ---
(all C14 items are clarifications of C11 features)


=== C17 (ISO 9899:2018) ===

C17 also contains only defect reports against C14/C11.
No new language features. No compiler work needed.


=== C23 (ISO 9899:2024) ===

C23 is a significant update. Many features are useful for porting.

--- Already done / unneeded ---

A. // comments                      [already worked in kencc]
B. u8 character constants           [can be added to lex.c alongside \uXXXX]
C. __has_include                    [cpp already handles this in APExp]
D. Removal of trigraphs             [kencc never had them]
E. true/false as keywords           [defined via _Bool/_Stdbool.h]

--- Not done ---

1. [[attributes]] syntax: [[nodiscard]], [[deprecated]], [[fallthrough]]
   EFFORT: small (ignore unknown attributes gracefully)
   WHERE: cc.y (attribute syntax in declarations/statements)
   NOTE: Very common in modern code. Safest approach: parse [[...]]
         and ignore unknown attributes rather than error.
         [[noreturn]] should map to _Noreturn behavior.

2. #elifdef / #elifndef preprocessor directives
   EFFORT: small
   WHERE: cpp/cpp.c (preprocessor directive handling)
   NOTE: Shorthand for #elif defined(...). Common in new code.

3. #warning directive
   EFFORT: trivial
   WHERE: cpp/cpp.c
   NOTE: Already commonly expected. One line of code.

4. Binary integer literals 0b101010
   EFFORT: trivial
   WHERE: lex.c (integer constant lexing, alongside 0x hex)

5. Digit separators in numeric literals: 1'000'000
   EFFORT: small
   WHERE: lex.c (skip ' between digits in numeric literals)
   NOTE: Common in newer code for readability.

6. typeof / typeof_unqual operators
   EFFORT: medium
   WHERE: cc.y (new unary expression), sub.c (type extraction)
   NOTE: __typeof__ already works in GCC; kencc may already have it.
         Check if __typeof__ is handled. If so, typeof is trivial alias.

7. constexpr for objects (not functions)
   EFFORT: medium
   WHERE: cc.y, dcl.c (new storage class)
   NOTE: Like 'static const' with mandatory constant initializer.
         Common in new portable code as replacement for #define.

8. nullptr keyword (null pointer constant)
   EFFORT: trivial
   WHERE: lex.c itab (map to OCONST 0 of type void*)
   NOTE: Very common in new C code. One entry in itab[].

9. auto type deduction (auto x = expr; deduces type)
   EFFORT: medium-large
   WHERE: dcl.c, com.c (infer type from initializer)
   NOTE: Repurposes the existing 'auto' keyword. Significant but
         increasingly needed for modern portable code.

10. Improved enums: enum E : int { ... } and enum E { A = 0u }
    EFFORT: small-medium
    WHERE: cc.y, dcl.c (enum base type)

11. char8_t type and u8 string literals as char8_t[]
    EFFORT: small
    WHERE: cc.h (new type), lex.c (u8"..." prefix)
    NOTE: Pair with uchar.h work from C11 item 6.

12. Variably-modified function parameters without VLAs
    EFFORT: small (already partially covered by VLA work)

13. <stdbit.h>: bit manipulation functions
    EFFORT: small (library)
    WHERE: new sys/include/ape/stdbit.h + lib/ap/misc/

14. #embed directive
    EFFORT: medium
    WHERE: cpp/cpp.c
    NOTE: Embeds binary file contents as integer sequence.
          Increasingly used for embedding resources.


=== Priority recommendation for APExp ===

HIGH (blocks real ported code frequently):
  C11-1: _Static_assert         -- very common in system headers
  C11-5: Anonymous structs/unions -- very common in system headers
  C23-1: [[attributes]] parsing  -- needed to not error on modern code
  C23-3: #warning                -- trivial, expected everywhere
  C23-4: Binary literals 0b...   -- increasingly common
  C23-8: nullptr                 -- trivial, common in new C code

MEDIUM (useful but workarounds exist):
  C11-2: _Alignas / _Alignof     -- needed for some SIMD/crypto code
  C11-3: _Generic                -- needed for tgmath.h
  C23-2: #elifdef/#elifndef      -- easy, common in new code
  C23-6: typeof                  -- check if __typeof__ already works
  C23-5: Digit separators        -- easy

LOW (rarely blocks, large effort):
  C11-4: _Atomic / stdatomic.h   -- stub is acceptable for most code
  C23-7: constexpr               -- medium effort
  C23-9: auto type deduction     -- large effort, rarely needed in C

SKIP (not worth the effort for APExp use case):
  C11-7: Annex K bounds checking
  C11-8: Annex L analyzability
  C14:   all (defect fixes only)
  C17:   all (defect fixes only)
